result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (5th or 6th) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (5th+ Offense)] and Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (5th+ Offense)]. The defendant was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (5th+ Offense)] and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (5th+ Offense)] was dismissed by the court.

  • Carrie J. Rosin was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (5th+ Offense)], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

DA Craig Lambert appears as Special Prosecutor for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Matousek.  No victim notification required.  Defendant plead no contest to Count 1 in 16CF5.  OWI 5th.  All other charges and tracking cases are dismissed outright.    Court reviewed the charge and possible penalties of the count the defendant plead to.   Defendant understood.  Felony warnings and deportation warning given.  Prior OWI convictions confirmed by the court with the defendant and Attorney Matousek.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  He understood. Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered her plea and waived her constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of OWI 5th contrary to 346.63(1)(a).  Joint recommendation for $3,000.00  fine, plus costs.  36 month driver's license revocation and ignition interlock devise.  Alcohol assessment and driver's safety plan.  1 year jail.  Attend a victim impact panel.  Defendant's father made a statement to the court.  Defendant exercised her right to allocution.  

Court ordered:  $3,000.00  fine, plus costs. $4863.00 total.  36 month driver's license revocation and ignition interlock devise requirement.  Alcohol assessment and driver's safety plan.  Attend a victim impact panel within 6 months.   File a certificate of attendance by May 1, 2018 with the Clerk of Court's office.  1 year jail to commence immediately.  First 48 hours to be served consecutively.   EMP allowed, according to jail rules.  Credit for 5 days.   Pay fine @ 100.00 per month, starting February 1, 2018.    Failure to pay any part of the fine and court costs will result in 30 days jail.

Covers 16CF05, 16CT04 and 16CF225.  Defendant shall not operate a motor vehicle on the highways.    Defendant shall not consume any alcohol unless a physician states in writing that the defendant is alcohol dependent and complete withdrawal could endanger the defendant's health or life. In this case a doctor's excuse must be submitted to the Jackson County Clerk of Court or the Jackson County Jail within 48 hours of the bond being signed. Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, bar areas of restaurants, or where available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located.  Not to be in any liquor areas in any stores or restaurants.  As a condition of your release, you must be available 24 hours per day, 7 days a week to submit to testing for alcohol when requested by a law enforcement officer or your probation agent. The defendant may submit to an alcohol test at the Jackson County Sheriff's Office or submit to a PBT by a law enforcement officer. Upon request, the defendant shall appear for and submit to testing within two (2) hours of the official's request.  May operate only a motor vehicle that has an IID installed and must operate during her occupational hours for work and for attending AA meetings and/or treatment appointments.  Defendant may be employed at a supper club or restaurant that serves alcohol.  May not consume alcohol.  May only be at the work premises for the work shift only.  Defendant to test once every 24 hours at the Jackson Counth Sheriff's Department kiosk.
